x4freetext: Experiment performed at the Argonne
Tandem Linac Accelerator System (ATLAS)
superconducting heavy ion accelerator
Enriched 208Pb target with
thickness of 49 mg/cm2. The effective target thickness
(the portion of the target where the beam energy went
from the incident energy of 785 MeV to the reaction
barrier energy 700.5MeV) was 3.113 mg/cm2.
Prompt gamma rays were detected using HPGe
detector array Gammasphere, which for this experiment
consisted of 90 Compton suppressed HPGe detectors.
With the beam on and average beam
current of 0.47 pnA., the spacing between the
accelerator  beam bursts was 824 ns. Triple gamma-
ray coincidence events (g-g-g ) were recorded. After
the irradiation was stopped, Gammasphere was switched
to singles mode and the target was counted for 39 h.
Then the target was removed from Gammasphere and gamma-
ray spectroscopy of the target radioactivities was
carried out using a well-calibrated Ge detector in the
ATLAS hot chemistry laboratory. The total observation
period was 5.3 days, during which time 15 measurements
of target radioactivity were made. The end of
bombardment (EOB) activities of the nuclides were used
to calculate absolute production cross sections. The
yields of ground state and isomeric states for a given
nuclide were summed to give a total nuclidic cross
section.
The analysis of the in-beam Gammasphere data was
carried out by construction of two g-g-g histograms.
One histogram was constructed using prompt gamma
decays recorded during the beam burst (IB), and the
other was constructed using delayed g decays recorded
between the beam bursts (OB). All of the individual
transition intensities from both the IB and OB
histograms were summed to give the total gamma yields
of each reaction product. Absolute cross sections were
determined using equations for growth and decay,
taking into account the beam intensities.
